AGI - The German Chancellor Olaf Scholz will now be visiting the South of Germany hit by floods, after days of heavy rains left much of the region under water causing the death of a rescuer while another is lost. Thousands of people were evacuated from their homes on weekends in the southern regions of Bavaria and Baden-Wurttemberg.
The situation continued to deteriorate last night and 800 other people were invited to leave their homes in the area of Ebenhausen-Werk, in Bavaria, where a dam gave way to the power of water. Also the district of Regensburg, where the Danube flows, has today joined the growing list of regions that declared the state of emergency due to the rising water.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Scholz is visiting the Reichertshofen area this morning in Bavaria, near where some of the worst floods occurred. The Chancellor is accompanied by the Interior Minister Nancy Faeser and the Bavarian Premier Markus Soeder. Yesterday, a 42-year volunteer firefighter was found dead after his boat had overturned during a rescue operation; another 22-year-old volunteer is missing for a similar accident.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Although the rain has decreased, floods have had an impact on transport: many trains have been deleted or recorded delays and in particular railway lines from Munich to Stuttgart, Nuremberg and Wurzburg are unusable according to the site of Deutsche Bahn. A landslide near Schwaebisch Gmuend on the night between Saturday and Sunday derailed a high-speed train between Stuttgart and Augusta, blocking the line but without any injuries.&nbsp;
